The desktop is a fight that IBM, however, is not giving up easily.

I do agree with you, that the AS/400 is one hell of an application
server, that it's correct for IBM to push that.

What is wrong is that the AS/400 will protect any investment you have on
MVS, or that it is a logical upgrade from AIX, as some others might think.

Both MVS and AIX are much closer to the traditional paradigms of computing
we know (S/360 and MVS actually helped define it.) The AS/400 takes quite
a radical approach or paradigm---everything is an object---that you
have to redefine what you expect from an OS---which in reality works much
like an object oriented database.

The AS/400 instead, can replace an MVS mainframe totally.  A few high end
machines connected via APPN will do quite nicely. Furthermore, it's a
breeze to use, and I mean literally, when compared to Unix, and even PC
OSes and NOSes.


