Have you read a recent article from Fortune?  It talks about mainframes
being back---with a vengeance.  It's not a short burst, it's not a short
trend, but it seems that it's here to stay.

1.) The growing awareness about the failings of the client server model.
It has not really proven it's cheaper, easier to administer, efficient,
reliable or as robust.  Actually it's proving to be far more kludgy.

2.) It has not proven it can replace mainframes as massively secure data
repositories.  In fact, the collection of data from networks helped fuel
the need to centralize data collection in one place for repository and
collection, while replacing mainframes have turned out to be so painful.

As a result, last year, IBM shipped more mainframe capacity than it had
for years, and it wasn't still enough, so much that Amdahl picked up the
business and went big red to big black overnight.  RS/6000 and AS/400
sales were also on the rise, but not even the high end RS/6000 and AS/400
helped stem that demand.

The only thing going out are character terminals, replaced by PCs and
network cards as the mainframe front end.


